	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New international framework proposed for commodities trade</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 February 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>On 9-10 December, ACP House, the Brussels home of the ACP Secretariat, hosted an international conference organised by the Common Fund for Commodities (CFC) under the title of ‘Promoting beneficial global financial and commodity market synergies’.</p><p>After opening addresses from CFC Managing Director Ali Mchumo, and Mohamed Ibn Chambas, Secretary-General of the ACP countries, the conference held sessions on ‘The case of excess volatility of commodity markets’, ‘Market volatility and emerging markets’, ‘Contagion between financial markets and commodity markets’, ‘The role of banks and regulators’ and ‘Doing the right thing’.</p><p>The centrepiece of the conference was an in-depth paper specially commissioned by the CFC from Professor Machiko Nissanke of the School of Oriental and African Studies at London University.</p><p>The paper, ‘Commodity markets and excess volatility’, gave a detailed analysis of trends in commodity prices since the nineteenth century and then discussed the present situation of commodity-dependent economies in Africa, the Caribbean and elsewhere.</p><p>Professor Nissanke said that under the prevailing international system, many of these countries were locked into an ‘international poverty trap’ due to their integration into the global economy. She attributed the recent heightened price instability on many commodity markets to the greater presence of financial investors, including their use of derivatives instruments on unregulated markets.</p><p>Professor Nissanke proposed the introduction of innovative schemes to reduce excess price volatility: her paper will shortly be available on a special conference website, 
<a href="http://cfc-brussels.org/" target="_blank">http://cfc-brussels.org/</a>, along with all the conference presentations. The presentations are to be published by the CFC as a book later in 2011.</p><p>One scheme, described in a paper by the International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI), recommends a combination of small physical food reserves with a ‘virtual’ international reserve facility for timely intervention on futures markets. The first such scheme could come under the World Food Programme, and the second might be funded by members of the G20 group of countries.</p><p>A new international framework would improve the share of benefits reaching producers and producing countries from their commodity sectors, Nissanke said. A global facility should run the food reserve scheme together with a new compensatory finance facility. She also considered that aid and debt contracts should be restructured to take each country’s specific situation into account, including its vulnerability to external shocks and systemic risks.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
