<a href="http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=MEMO/10/504&amp;format=HTML&amp;aged=1&amp;language=EN&amp;guiLanguage=en" target="_self">http://europa.eu/rapid/pressReleasesAction.do?reference=MEMO/10/504&amp;...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The twin food and financial crises of 2008 reopened an old debate about commodity price instability and its impact on developing countries. Despite the conference title of ‘Promoting beneficial global financial and commodity market synergies’, the main theme of the Common Fund for Commodities conference at ACP headquarters was price volatility.</p><p>In fact, two separate debates have developed since 2008, one of these about the reasons for the greater recent volatility in commodity prices and what needs to be done about it, and the other about policies for food security in the wake of the global price increases in 2008 and again in the second half of 2010.</p><p>Professor Nissanke’s paper emphasised the role played by financial investors and speculators in recent price volatility, while other commentators suggested more ‘fundamental’ supply and demand causes, such as the increase in demand from China and other emerging countries, the lack of investment in new production after 25 years of low commodity prices, and in food commodities the diversion of land to grow biofuels.</p><p>While Professor Nissanke favours global policies such as food reserves and compensation schemes, discussions in the most influential circles have centred on increasing food production, particularly with the use of biotechnology, such as genetically modified crops. Still others argue that there was a failure of modern systems of agriculture and call for greater use of diverse and resilient traditional food crops, rather than globally traded cereals such as wheat, rice and maize. This, however, raises issues related to the effective commercialisation of more resilient traditional food crops, which may require investment not only in production but also in processing, marketing and even product innovation.</p><p>In the EU, current thinking is focusing on investment in the production side and in facilitating trade, so that food supplies can flow more easily from food-surplus to food-deficit areas (given the likely increased frequency of weather-related production disruptions). Discussions on more effective regulation of speculative investment in food commodity markets form part of wider EU efforts to regulate financial speculation. More directly, internally the EU is looking at two types of measure to reduce the impact of price volatility on the underlying production base. The first of these is redefining its ‘safety-net’ policy to avoid influencing price formation while ensuring that price volatility does not undermine the production base. The second type of measure is strengthening the functioning of specific food supply chains, where inequalities in power relationships along the supply chain mean that primary producers carry a disproportionate burden of price volatility. It is unclear whether the EU is willing to support the extension of these approaches to addressing price volatility on international commodity markets.</p>
		</div>
		
